comment: Me: "Hmm... an 850W power supply might be overkill for my build... but I can get it for a few dollars cheaper than a 750W if I get this one from Amazon..."
LTT's latest video: "Two 3090's in SLI and a 10900K are tripping overvolt protection on a 1000W power supply."
Suddenly I feel confident in my purchase, especially since I plan on upgrading the processor / GPU at some point in the future xD
Yeah, you're better just over speccing a PSU than not, you're just buying more capability going higher wattage.
Also any PSU using a fraction of its capacity is more efficient (less overhead watt burn) if running under it's full capacity.
Like how brakes on cars 'fade' when overused/stressed reduce stopping distance.
Increased heat causes reduced functionality at the fringes of designed capacity.
Hence why bigger brakes are an upgrade that enhances stopping power and reduces brake fatigue.
Don't always need it, but it sure is great when you do.
LTT was testing RTX 3090's in SLI for reasons
And combined with the 10900k, it was enough to trip the overcurrent protection on their 1000W power supply, lol
suffice to say, my power supply should comfortably handle a 3080 and any ryzen processor I choose, and have plenty of wattage to spare for degredation over time

Yeah, it might just be the architecture is due for a refresh I remember 2010-11 the reviews of nvidia cards that era were like, "it sucks power, and it's 1000 degrees, but boy does it kick out great frame rates"

Lol, looks like Stadia is gonna die soon

Google is releasing a new Chromecast and discontinuing the old one (which is a necessity if you want to use Stadia on a TV)
BUT Stadia is not officially supported on the new Chromecast... and you can only get the old one by buying one of the founder's editions of Stadia that ships a Stadia controller
You can try side-loading Stadia onto the new Chromecast, but it might either act janky or refuse to work at all.

So... let's think about this.  Goodle is releasing new hardware which is essential for Stadia to work at home.  But they aren't supporting Stadia at launch.  Meanwhile, alternatives like Geforce Now and Steam Link are supported on the new device.
It's almost like Stadia is failing hard and they're hoping it'll just die off and people will forget about it.
I remember finding a Stadia fan boy on Twitter, oh man was this guy sucking Google's D HARD.
Man is he gonna be devastated when everyone finally tells him "I told you so.  For months.  But you didn't listen."
Technical issues abound, nonsensical business model, Google's prevalence for bailing on new products / services if they aren't immediately a smash hit :/
The wonderful life of corporate business...
We all saw this coming.  The only way I'll be shocked is if Google reverses course and starts pumping resources into Stadia again
But given how it's going and how they've behaved in the past, I feel like this new product is well on its way to the Google Graveyard.
In other news, the new Marvel's Avengers game is going the way of Anthem
the problem is it's still too early for streamed games
give it another decade or so for internet to catch up
It's not even that.  Google's business model made 0 sense
First off, you can ONLY stream.  Other services give you the option to either stream, or download the games you want to play
Second, you pay for ACCESS.  While there is a free version that limits things like resolution, framerate, quality, etc, to get the better experience, you pay a subscription.
Third, and this ties into the second point, you don't own games on Stadia.  You have to pay for every single game you want to play, like you're buying to own.  But you're buying access to that title.
If Stadia is ever killed off, every single purchase you make is thrown in the garbage, and there's nothing you can do.
I feel sorry for the people who like Stadia, I really do.  They just don't see that they've thrown their money away.
